 table, calculated sensitivities, specificities with their 95% confidence intervals. Used QUADAS-2 tool plus additional items to assess methodological quality.\nMain results:\nOne study applicable to first objective (A): Sensitivity and specificity for diagnosis of DLB in participants meeting clinical criteria or NINCDS-ADRDA criteria; Semiquantitative vs visual analysis; High risk of bias in participant selection and index test domains. Sensitivity 1.00 (95% CI: 0.66-1.00), specificity 0.92 (95% CI: 0.64-1.00) for semiquantitative; Sensitivity 0.86 (95% CI: 0.42-1.00), specificity 0.83 (95% CI: 0.52-0.98) for visual analysis.\nSecond objective (B): Sensitivity and specificity in baseline clinical suspicion; Semiquantitative had sensitivity 1.00 (95% CI: 0.63-1.00), specificity 1.00 (95% CI: 0.59-1.00); Visual analysis had lower accuracy with sensitivity 0.83 (95% CI: 0.36-1.00) and specificity 0.71 (95% CI: 0.29-0.96).\nAuthors' conclusions:\nOnly one study used neuropathological reference standard to assess accuracy of DAT imaging for DLB diagnosis; Small study size leads to imprecise sensitivity and specificity estimates; Suggests DAT imaging is more accurate than clinical diagnosis.\nNo studies using neuropathological reference standard have addressed the scenario where DAT imaging is considered a diagnostic test in people with possible DLB or assessed accuracy in people with mild dementia. However, included data suggest normal 123I-FP-CIT SPECT may be an accurate means of excluding DLB in cases of moderately severe dementia and strong suspicion.\nSemiquantitative ratings appeared more accurate than visual ratings in all analyses."}
